So ecastfir. Castor, from which ecastor is derived, formed its genitive Castoris in old Latin (Quintil. Just. 1. 5. 60): so Hectoris in Ennius. 2. 2. 82:

-Ur. The last syllable of iyitur is apparently long. Amph. 2. 2. 87: Verum non est puero gravida. Quid igitur? Insania..

Ritschl here defended the lengthening by the strong pause at change of speakers, as he defended dicere, supra. And this view of syllaba anceps at change of speakers ought to commend itself to those who hold, as I think they ought, that Plautus permitted hiatus at change of speakers. See under Hiatus, infra, p.
